\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms when demand increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Initial shock changes one or more demand components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive demand shock is a shock that increases domestic demand for given
 prices.
 The demand curve shifts right.
 This occurs through changes in private consumption, public consumption,
 investments, exports, or imports.
 The shock can be direct, as with a shock to government consumption, but
 it is often indirect, as with shocks to the income tax, which change household
 income.
 Regardless, the way the different demand shocks propagate through the model
 economy is similar, and we discuss it in this section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased demand leads to increased sector production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When demand increases, production from different sectors will increase via
 the input / output system.
 For given output prices and unit costs, firms will want to meet the increased
 demand to increase profits.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased sectoral production leads to increased production inputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To increase production, firms must increase their capacity utilization and
 input of intermediates, labor, and capital.
 Firms invest in capital based on their expectations for production in the
 coming periods.
 In the short and medium run, there are decreasing returns to scale due
 to installation costs, while in the long run, there are constant returns
 to scale.
 Capacity utilization means that production in the short run is not only
 affected by the amount of production inputs used.
 In this manner, output in the individual sectors can increase more than
 factor input in the short term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Time-to-build and installation costs on capital mean that user costs on
 capital increase in the short run relative to other inputs.
 The K/L ratios in the individual sectors decrease.
 In the short run, it is thus easier to increase factor input from labor
 and intermediates compared to capital.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased intermediate inputs leads to increased imports and domestic sectoral
 output
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased demand for intermediate inputs results in increased demand for
 goods and services from other sectors and imports.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased capital demand leads to increased investments from imports and
 domestic sectoral output 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased investment also results in increased demand for production from
 domestic sectors and imports that deliver inputs to investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased labor demand leads to increased wages, employment and labor supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The labor market is a search-labor market, where annual negotiations for
 a share of the wage contracts determine the wage.
 To increase employment, firms must hire more employees and post more vacancies.
 The more vacancies posted relative to the number of job seekers, the more
 difficult it is to get a match by a vacancy posting.
 The marginal cost of hiring thus increases for firms.
 In return, it becomes easier for the job seekers to get a match.
 The expected marginal gain from applying for a job increases, causing household
s to increase the effective labor supply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased marginal cost of hiring causes the marginal cost of labor to increase.
 It provides a larger wedge between the marginal cost of new employees the
 firm is willing to pay and the salary existing employees receive.
 This increases the bargaining power of existing employees, which puts upward
 pressure on salaries.
 Wages adapt sluggishly and gradually contribute to increasing the marginal
 cost of labor.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased employment and wages leads to higher household income and increased
 demand for private consumption and housing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased employment and wages increase household income.
 Households spread consumption throughout their life and save something
 for inheritance, considering the relative prices and expectations of future
 wealth and income.
 Habit consumption provides a more gradual adjustment, and the benefit of
 wealth incl., including inheritance, ensures that they save when old and
 do not borrow too much when young.
 Reference consumption relative to liquid income (Keynesian consumption)
 ensures empirically realistic marginal propensities to consume out of income
 increases, which ensures realistic short-run consumption properties.
 Furthermore, the effect will depend on which age groups experience the
 income increase, as younger age groups in MAKRO have a higher marginal
 propensity to consume.
 The increase in private consumption reflects an increase in consumption,
 excluding housing and housing consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased housing demand leads to increased housing prices and investments
 in housing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The increased housing demand results primarily in higher prices because
 the supply of housing changes slowly.
 The marginal price for increasing the housing volume is very high in the
 short run because houses embody land that exists in rigid supply, and land
 and other inputs are not strong substitutes in producing the final housing
 good.
 The housing volume thus only changes slightly in the short run, while the
 house price is quite volatile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased housing prices leads to increased liquidity and demand for private
 consumption and housing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher housing prices lead to a redistribution of wealth from those who
 purchase houses to those who sell.
 In isolation, this prompts a negative effect on private consumption, as
 home buyers in MAKRO (typically younger households) have a higher marginal
 propensity to consume than home sellers (typically older households) do.
 However, this effect is dominated by the fact that all households can borrow
 through a mortgage.
 Overall, this mechanism means that increased housing prices lead to a higher
 propensity to consume as the liquidity gain of higher house prices enters
 into the Keynesian reference consumption income term.
 There is thus an amplifying effect on consumption through demand shocks
 via increased loan financing in the housing market - a so-called financial
 accelerator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased production leads to a gradual increase in output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing marginal vacancy posting costs and capital installation costs
 mean that firms' unit costs rise in the short run.
 The firm has an additional way of increasing output in the short run: to
 increase its factor utilization.
 However, increased capacity utilization today must be compensated for in
 the future by bringing down utilization again.
 Overall, firms' unit costs are rising, eroding their profit margins and
 putting upward pressure on output prices.
 However, the increase in prices is gradual due to price-setting rigidity..
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher output prices leads to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input / output system mechanically links higher output prices to higher
 demand prices based on input shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased prices dampens the quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased prices reduce the quantity demanded.
 The increased prices mean lower demand in the market for goods and services.
 The effect is modest for intermediates, as the substitution elasticities
 are typically small.
 Investments are also generally not very sensitive to changes in investment
 prices and react more due to lower production due to the fall in other
 demand components.
 Private consumption reacts - primarily as a reaction to the fall in real
 income.
 Exports are much more sensitive to changing prices.
 The reaction is only gradual, but in the long run, exports will change
 significantly due to changes in relative prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, rising prices significantly affect domestic demand through
 the effect of relative prices on import content.
 Thus, the demand for domestic production of intermediates or private consumptio
n will fall, even though rising prices only affect the general demand for
 these components to a lesser extent.
 As with exports, this reaction to relative prices is gradual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Full crowding out in employment for permanent demand shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A permanent exogenous increase in domestic demand will result in crowding
 out via foreign trade, improved terms of trade, and higher real wages.
 In the short run, price and wage rigidities will increase employment.
 In the long run, however, structural employment will be re-established.
 Higher domestic demand pushes up domestic prices and reduces exports.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Wages will typically grow more than domestic output prices, so that product
 real wages will grow.
 This is because the user cost of capital in the long run mainly depends
 on the investment price.
 Due to the high import content of the investments, these investment prices
 will grow less than the sectors’ output prices.
 This causes product-real-user cost to fall.
 In the long-run equilibrium, this will mean that real product wages grow
 and that there will be a substitution towards capital.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms when supply increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply decrease prices for given demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A positive supply shock decreases prices for any given quantity produced.
 The supply curve shifts right.
 There is typically an effect via the production costs of the firm as with
 increased labor supply (lowers costs of labor), increased productivity
 (reduces effective costs of one or more production inputs), lower financial
 costs (lower capital costs), or lower foreign prices (lower intermediate
 input or investment costs).
 With output prices being set as a markup over costs, these prices also
 fall.
 Shocks to foreign prices also affect the demand prices directly through
 imports.
 Furthermore, shocks to foreign prices affect demand through the import
 shares and exports, both affected by foreign prices.
 Financial shocks are also often more than a pure shock to economic costs,
 and an interest rate shock will, for example, change the income flow, wealth,
 and hence the demand of the households.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we focus on labor supply and productivity shocks.
 Shocks to foreign prices and financial shocks are described in later sections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply leads to fewer production inputs for given production and
 lower unit costs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A productivity shock lowers unit production costs, and labor, capital, and
 materials inputs are all reduced for a given production.
 The input of the more productive input is reduced as it is possible to
 produce the same with less input, and this is not dominated by substitution
 effects as all substitution elasticities in the production are less than
 or close to one.
 Input of the other factors is reduced due to substitution as the more productiv
e factor has become cheaper in effective units.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total labor input consists of workers times hours worked times individual
 productivity.
 Hours worked depend on taxes, wages, and a preference shifter for hours.
 Both preferences and taxes can be shocked.
 In addition, there is a preference shifter specific to the disutility of
 search.
 Reducing the disutility of search will increase the number of matches per
 vacancy posted by the firms and will decrease the marginal costs of hiring
 and, hence, the unit cost of firms.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower unit costs leads to lower output prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lower unit costs cause the firms to lower prices.
 The increase is gradual due to price adjustment costs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower output prices leads to lower demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input/output system mechanically links lower output prices to lower
 demand prices based on input shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Lower prices increases quantity demand over time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lower prices increase the quantity demand.
 As described in the subsection 'Increased demand,' prices dampen demand
 over time primarily through foreign trade - but with the reversed sign.
 The effects of higher demand are described in the section 'Fundamental
 mechanisms when demand increase'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Full crowding out in the unemployment rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some permanent supply shocks can change the structural unemployment rate
 (e.g., changing the compensation rate of unemployment), but most shocks do
 not, and none of those mentioned above do.
 Increased demand will, over time, increase employment until the structural
 unemployment rate is unchanged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increasing hours or participation will make domestic prices and real wages
 fall if public consumption or foreign demand is exogenous.
 The reason is similar to the mechanism described under the demand shocks.
 The larger labor supply will result in more domestic goods being produced
 in the long run.
 Domestic prices must fall to sell more goods in the export market.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased supply will over time cause scale effects in exports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
