\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms when foreign prices increases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Initial shock increases import prices and/or export competing prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In MAKRO, foreign prices can be divided into two main groups: Import prices
 and prices on goods/services that compete with domestic exports, henceforth
 called export competing prices.
 They are both affected by the exogenous oil price and an exogenous foreign
 price, excluding direct and indirect effects from the oil price.
 It is possible to shock the oil and/or foreign prices.
 It is also possible to exogenize and shock some or all of the import and/or
 export competing prices directly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A higher oil price affects all import and export competing prices, but energy
 prices are affected more.
 A higher foreign price excluding oil also affects all import and export
 competing prices, but energy prices are affected less.
 Realistic shocks to the oil price or foreign price should affect the foreign
 demand market and interest rates as movements in different foreign variables
 are correlated.
 In MAKRO, these are exogenous and considered constant in the description
 of the shock effects.
 A realistic foreign shock (general equilibrium for the foreign economy)
 moves all these components.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher export competing prices increase exports
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only effect of higher export competing prices is to increase demand
 for exports.
 For the Danish economy, this is a positive demand shock to exports and
 follows the mechanisms described above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher import prices reduce imports and increase domestic demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every type of demand has inputs from potentially all sectors and from imports
 or domestic production.
 These inputs are cells in the input-output (IO) matrix, either positive
 or zero.
 Import shares are endogenous and respond to prices unless imports are zero
 for a given product.
 If the import price increases relative to the domestic price in a given
 sector, all IO-cells representing input from this sector (that are not
 0 or 1) will have a lower import share.
 This substitution effect tends to increase domestic demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The import share of energy is constant and not affected by relative prices.
 The production of extraction is also exogenous.
 The only relevant sectors affected by substitution are manufacturing and
 services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher import prices lead to higher demand prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The input-output system mechanically links higher output prices to higher
 demand prices based on input shares.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased demand prices lead to lower domestic quantity demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Increased prices affect domestic demand as described under the demand shocks
 in the subsection 'Increased demand' prices dampens quantity demand over
 time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Sign of net effects from increased import prices on demand differs for demand
 components
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand for specific components may increase or decrease following higher
 import prices.
 The substitution effect increases demand for manufacturing and services
 while the effect from increased demand prices lowers demand for all demand
 components.
 As manufacturing and services might be close substitutes to other components
 with low substitution, the net effect on these in the different cells may
 also be negative.
 An example is input of domestic services to private consumption of cars.
 Private consumption of cars has two inputs: Manufacturing with an import
 share of 1 and services with an import share of 0.
 Import shares of 1 and 0 indicate that no substitution takes place at cell
 level.
 This means for higher import prices of manufacturing the demand will decrease
 by the same relative amount for imported manufacturing and domestic services.
 There are also examples where the net effect is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Higher material prices increase unit costs and give substitution towards
 labor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Demand prices increase when import prices increase.
 This includes the price of intermediate inputs.
 When these prices increase the unit costs of production increase in all
 sectors.
 The effects are the same as described in the section 'Fundamental mechanisms
 when supply increase' - with the opposite sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firms will substitute away from intermediate inputs as they are relatively
 more expensive compared to labor.
 Capital may become more or less costly as it is increased through investment
 with imported inputs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Substitution towards labor dampens negative effects on wages and employment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The substitution towards labor dampens the opposing general equilibrium
 effects on employment and wages from the higher prices.
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Fundamental mechanisms for financial shocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Initial shock changes returns and asset prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financial shocks affect firms and households.
 Changes in asset prices and asset returns affect private income, wealth,
 and consumption.
 Changes to finance costs affect firms immediately in all their forward-looking
 decisions.
 Financial shocks can be shocks to the ECB key interest rate, foreign stock
 prices, asset-specific risk premia, etc.
 Changes to interest rates and risk premia will work through the discount
 factors firms and households use.
 Jumps in foreign stock prices work first through a wealth effect but have
 other nonlinear effects through the specification of household utility.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Households have wealth in utility and bequest utility.
 Refer also to the MAKRO documentation for more info.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Returns and asset prices are affected and will in turn affect household
 demand
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Higher returns on assets will increase net returns for agents with positive
 portfolios and can affect the savings behavior of households.
 This will, in turn, impact private consumption and housing demand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased finance costs of housing will decrease demand for housing investments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An increase in the cost of finance will increase the user cost for the relevant
 real variables.
 Housing is financed primarily through real estate bonds, but also through
 other financial savings.
 The last is affected by the household's marginal return on savings, determined
 by the return on assets and portfolio composition.
 Factors that increase housing finance, i.e., the real estate bond rate and
 other rates of return (also through composition), will increase the user
 cost of housing.
 This will, for given prices, lead to lower housing demand.
 This will then work like a negative shock to investments in housing through
 mechanisms described in the section 'Fundamental mechanisms when demand
 increases'.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Increased finance costs of firm capital will increase unit costs and substitutio
n will decrease firm investments
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The user cost for firm investments will also be affected by financial costs.
 Firm investments are financed partly by borrowing and partly by issuing
 new stock.
 The cost of finance is, hence, a weighted average of the interest rate
 and the return on stocks.
 A higher interest rate and future return on domestic stocks will increase
 the user cost of firm investments.
 This will increase the unit costs and act like a negative supply shock
 described in the section 'Fundamental mechanisms when supply increases.'
 Furthermore, there will be substitution away from capital.
 This will decrease firm investment for given production.
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The reaction of the public sector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The shocks analyzed below will change the basis of government revenue and
 expenditure.
 Given unchanged public consumption and transfer and tax rates, this makes
 fiscal policy either sustainable or unsustainable.
 Therefore, the public sector is forced to react by changing tax rates,
 transfer rates, and public spending.
 In many models, there is an endogenous public response function, such that
 the public sector automatically reconciles revenue and expenditure via
 pre-determined rules.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
MAKRO is to be used in connection with fiscal policy planning, and therefore,
 it does not contain an endogenous financing constraint.
 However, this does not mean that fiscal policy does not have to be sustainable.
 In analyzing shocks, we often see the mechanisms more clearly in unfinanced
 shocks.
 Financed shocks with fiscal policy balance are, however, more realistic.
 In MAKRO, the default is to finance shocks so that the fiscal sustainability
 indicator is unchanged by making a permanent lump-sum transfer between
 the households and the public sector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether or not (and how) a budget balance is financed matters.
 MAKRO has forward-looking households and firms and, therefore, a degree
 of Ricardian equivalence, which makes the effects of this choice far from
 trivial.
 
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
A brief note on the sectors in in MAKRO
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 9 sectors in MAKRO.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This compares with the 12 sectors in ADAM.
 Construction, sea transport, agriculture, extraction and housing are identical.
 The energy sector in MAKRO is the sum of the energy sector and the refinery
 sector in ADAM, while the manufacturing sector is the sum of the food sector
 and diverse manufacturing in ADAM.
 Finally, the public sector in ADAM is equal to public administration and
 services, while the private industry is financial services, other private
 services and public services minus public administration and services.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several factors make some sectors less central to shock analysis than others.
 For example, the housing sector is driven solely by household demand and
 draws almost exclusively from the construction sector.
 The extraction industry is exogenously given, and production is thus not
 affected by shocks.
 Maritime transport (shipping) and agriculture are small industries with
 a limited share of GVA and employment, meaning their role is limited when
 describing the aggregate effects of shocks.
 This is especially true for maritime transport, where exports - due to
 high import content - are largely independent of Danish prices.
 The energy sector is interesting when energy taxes change, while it does
 not play a significant role in many other shocks.
 Although the public sector is large, it is exogenous and therefore only
 vital if it is shocked directly.
 Thus, the two main sectors are (private) services and manufacturing.
 Services are essential because of their size: they account for almost half
 of GVA, over half of employment, and approximately one-third of aggregate
