 gives an overview of which sectoral output prices affect the prices of
 materials, private consumption, public consumption, investment, and exports.
 Generally, intermediate input prices are affected mainly by services, imports,
 and manufacturing.
 The price of private consumption excl.
 housing is primarily affected by services and imports.
 The housing deflator - used in the empirical calculation of total private
 consumption - is determined based on imputed regulated rents and is generally
 unaffected by shocks.
 The deflator for public consumption is determined primarily based on the
 output price of public production.
 The investment price of machinery capital is determined primarily based
 on the prices of services, manufacturing, and imports.
 In contrast, the price of building investments is primarily determined
 based on the price of construction and services.
 In isolation, the price of the construction sector is essential for the
 investment price of buildings.
 However, this price is, in isolation, not so important for the rest of
 the economy, as buildings only make up a small part of firm costs, and
 user costs in the short run primarily reflect installation costs.
 Export prices are mainly affected by manufacturing, services, and maritime
 shipping prices.
 However, as the price of shipping is almost unaffected by domestic conditions,
 this is not so important for the volume of exports for most shocks.
